'''Tony Tarzell Yarber''' (born April 16, 1978) is an American pastor, educator and politician in [[Jackson, Mississippi]]. In April 2014 he was elected as Mayor of Jackson in a special election following the death in office of [[Chokwe Lumumba]].<ref name="Barnes1">{{cite web|last=Barnes|first=Dustin|title=Yarber New Jackson Mayor|url=http://www.clarionledger.com/story/news/2014/04/23/yarber-victory/8038901/|publisher=Clarion-Ledger| date=April 22, 2014}}</ref>  A native of Jackson and experienced city councillor, Yarber is noted for his passion for youth causes, and has been described as "a consensus builder".<ref name="Lucas">{{cite web | last = Lucas | first = Sherry | title = Mayoral Race: Personal Profile of Tony Yarber | publisher = Clarion-Ledger | date = April 20, 2014 | url = http://www.clarionledger.com/story/news/2014/04/19/mayoral-race-personal-profile-tony-yarber/7922279/}}</ref>  He was succeeded as Mayor of Jackson by his predecessor's son Chokwe Antar Lumumba on July 3, 2017.<ref>http://www.wapt.com/article/lumumba-to-take-oath-of-office/10253701</ref>

==Career and personal life==
Yarber was born in Jackson, Mississippi to George and Deloris Yarber in 1978, and grew up in the city's Westside Community.<ref name="Lucas"/><ref name="CJM1">{{cite web | title = Tony Yarber | publisher = City of Jackson, Mississippi | url = https://ms-jackson.civicplus.com/index.aspx?NID=533 | accessdate = April 2014}}</ref>  He attended [[Forest Hill High School]] in Jackson.<ref>{{cite web | last1 = Ferretti | first1 =Haley | last2 = Nave | first2 = R.L. | title = A Hands-On Tony Yarber Administration? | publisher = Jackson Free Press | date = April 23, 2014 | url = http://www.jacksonfreepress.com/news/2014/apr/23/hands-tony-yarber-administration/}}</ref>

Yarber received a B.S. in Elementary Education from the [[University of Southern Mississippi]] and an M.S. in Education Administration and Supervision from [[Jackson State University]].<ref name="CJM1"/> He has taught school and served as an elementary school principal. Yarber served as a committee member for the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools.<ref name="CJM1"/>

He is also Pastor and Founder of the non-denominational Relevant Empowerment Church, started in 2008.<ref name="Lucas"/> He has served on the Board of Directors for Relevant Ministries.<ref name="CJM1"/>

Yarber has a black belt in [[ninjutsu]].<ref name="Lucas"/>  He is married and has three children.<ref name="CJM1"/>

In August 2016, a lawsuit was filed by Yarber's former executive assistant Kimberly Bracey, who accused Yarber of firing her when she turned down his sexual advances.  Yarber denied the allegations.<ref>{{cite web | last = Kenney | first = David | title = Mayor Yarber Responds to Sex Allegations | publisher = Msnewsnow | date = August 26, 2016 | url = http://www.msnewsnow.com/story/32852233/mayor-yarber-responds-to-sex-allegations}}</ref>

==Civic achievements==
Yarber is a founding member of Alignment Jackson, a non-profit organization for improving student achievement.<ref name="ATM">{{cite web | title = About the Mayor | publisher = City of Jackson | url = https://ms-jackson.civicplus.com/index.aspx?nid=245 | accessdate = April 2014}}</ref>

He was the second Vice-President of the Mississippi Black Caucus of Locally Elected Officials.<ref name="ATM"/>

==Elected office==

===City Councillor===
In 2009, Yarber entered city politics, running for the Jackson City Council from Ward 6. He became City Council Vice President in 2011, and President in 2012. In 2013, Yarber served as Chair of the Budget Committee, and the Education/Youth Ad Hoc Committee.<ref name="ATM"/>

===Mayor===
Yarber was elected Mayor of Jackson on April 22, 2014, in a runoff election against Chokwe Antar Lumumba, son of deceased former mayor [[Chokwe Lumumba]].<ref name="Barnes1"/>

Yarber stated that his goals as mayor will be to improve customer service for residents, and to attract new business   Yarber also discussed Jackson's potential for growth as an entertainment hub, and as a "medical corridor"  .<ref name="Lucas"/>".<ref>{{cite web | last = Barnes | first = Dustin | title = Mayor Tony Yarber Preaches Plans for Jackson | publisher = ''Clarion-Ledger'' | date = April 24, 2014 | url = http://www.clarionledger.com/story/news/2014/04/24/mayor-elect-tony-yarber-take-oath-office/8105543/ }}</ref>

On May 2, 2017, Yarber was soundly defeated by [[Chokwe Antar Lumumba]] in the primary for the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[List of mayors of Jackson, Mississippi|mayor]] of Jackson, receiving 5% to Lumumba's 55%.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/mississippi/articles/2017-05-03/some-mayors-defeated-in-mississippi-municipal-primaries |title=Some Mayors Defeated in Mississippi Municipal Primaries |date=2017-05-03 |website=US News and World Report |access-date=2017-05-04}}</ref>

